<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 92 / International Company News: Aetna Life &amp; Casualty improves
to Dollars 207m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AETNA Life &amp; Casualty, the largest shareholder-owned insurer in the US,
improved its profits performance in the first quarter of 1992 following
reduced losses from its property-related holdings and asset sale proceeds.
The company reported a Dollars 207m profit after tax in the first three
months, compared with Dollars 137m a year earlier. The improvement derived
from a turnround on net realised capital gains - with Aetna chalking up a
Dollars 76m profit after tax this time, compared with a Dollars 16m loss a
year ago. The company said without this its results would have been lower.
Like most of the large US composites, Aetna has been faced by souring real
estate investments recently, but yesterday it said that realised capital
losses from additions to reserves for mortgage and property write-downs were
Dollars 41m, against Dollars 52m a year ago.
Realised gains of Dollars 117m more than offset this - with Dollars 50m
coming from the sale of a portion of the company's interest in MBIA, the
bond insurer.
On the commercial property-casualty side, Aetna's first quarter earnings
were Dollars 60m, compared with Dollars 33m a year ago, but this included
net realised capital gains of Dollars 37m against Dollars 1m in the first
three months of 1991.
</TEXT>
