FT  24 APR 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow rallies after early fall
with drug stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
SHARE PRICES recovered yesterday afternoon as investors turned their
attention to cyclical stocks, following a morning sell-off in drug issues
which depressed US equities for most of the day in a market that was already
nervous following the flood of corporate results, writes Karen Zagor in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed a net 9.84 up at 3,348.61 after
having fallen more than 25 points at midsession. New York SE volume was a
fairly heavy 237.9m shares. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was
finally 1.79 ahead at 411.60 but the Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter
stocks shed 2.18 to 576.05.
In addition to the pressure from the quarterly corporate results, the market
was depressed by higher yields for longer-dated bonds. The yield of the
Treasury's 30-year bond continued to climb above the 8 per cent mark in the
morning following a report that initial jobless claims had fallen in a week
when economists had expected an increase. In late trading, the long bond was
quoted  3/16 down to yield 8.04 per cent after falling about  5/8 earlier in
the day.
Big board trading was dominated by pharmaceutical stocks. Johnson &amp; Johnson
tumbled Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 90 7/8 , reflecting disappointment with its
first-quarter results. The healthcare products company had a net income of
Dollars 464m or Dollars 1.38 a share, compared with Dollars 418m or Dollars
1.25 a share a year ago. The 11 per cent improvement was weaker than
expected. Sales increased by about 7 per cent to Dollars 3.36bn from the
year earlier figure of Dollars 3.15bn.
Shares in Merck also took a beating, although the company had no corporate
developments or news to report. The issue lost almost Dollars 5 before
recovering somewhat to close Dollars 2 5/8 lower at Dollars 139 3/4 .
Among other actively traded pharmaceutical stocks, Glaxo Holdings declined
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 25 5/8 but Bristol-Myers Squibb ended Dollars  3/8
ahead at Dollars 73.
Citicorp shares, which initially gained about 13 per cent after the bank
posted strong first-quarter results on Tuesday, started to correct
yesterday, with the issue slipping Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 19. Trading was
also active in Chase Manhattan, which rose Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 27.
A flood of results from technology companies fuelled active trading in the
sector. Tandem Computers slipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 12 3/8 following
second-quarter earnings of 8 cents a share, against 17 cents.
In the secondary market, Sun Microsystems rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 27
1/2 , reflecting the company's better than expected third-quarter income of
60 cents a share, compared with 56 cents a year earlier.
Canada
TORONTO stocks put on a steadier performance yesterday, helped by some
recovery in bank, real estate and construction issues.
Traders said that nervousness over the debt troubles of Olympia &amp; York had
eased, after the company said it had arranged a loan of USDollars 20m.
The composite index picked up 3.7 to close at 3,371.5, but declining issues
outnumbered advances by 306 to 245. Trading volume amounted to 28.9m shares.
Financial services had the day's best gain, up 1.1 per cent. The real estate
and construction index recovered 0.6 per cent.
BCE lost CDollars  1/2 to CDollars 44 3/8 . The company's BCE Telecom
International unit said it agreed to acquire a controlling interest in East
London Telecommunications, a British cable television company.
