<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / PowerGen nears radical shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POWERGEN has won backing from union leaders for a radical shake-up of pay
and collective bargaining procedures. It is the first UK electricity company
to win union approval on a local pay and conditions package after the
break-up of national arrangements.
The proposals include harmonisation of terms and conditions for all
employees, increasingly flexible working and introduction of 'single-table
bargaining' - the company's six unions negotiating together rather than in
the four forums under the national negotiating machinery.
If the company's 6,500 employees agree to the changes, many will move to
higher salaries. Nalgo, the public-services union, estimates that clerical
assistants and typists on Pounds 9,631 will receive Pounds 1,087 and
computer operators on Pounds 15,943 will receive Pounds 450 on top of the
5.5 per cent agreed in the national pay talks.
Also, all employees will have one-off payments of Pounds 400 plus 2 per cent
of salary for moving to the new structure.
All 18 UK electricity companies are in talks about changed pay systems after
giving notice that this year's national negotiations would be the last. Most
want single-table bargaining, although National Power, the biggest
generator, is among those which want to retain separate negotiations for
different groups of staff.
Like PowerGen, all companies will seek to negotiate pay systems that would
exclude possible claims from predominantly female groups for pay equal with
that of male staff.
Mr John Hart, PowerGen personnel director, said the new structure would
increase potential for teamwork and flexibility.
Members of Nalgo and the other five unions will be balloted on the offer.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
