<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / Electricity surplus of 60 per cent is predicted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND and Wales will have a 60 per cent surplus of electricity by 1997,
the National Grid Company (NGC), which manages the countries' electricity
system, disclosed in its annual statement yesterday.
More than 10,000MW of plant - the equivalent of 10 medium-size power
stations - would have to close to achieve a more reasonable 30 per cent
margin, the company's figures show.
That will support British Coal's fears that the many gas stations being
built will force older coal-fired stations to close.
Twenty-eight power stations are due to be built in England and Wales by
1997, the company said. All except the Sizewell B nuclear station will run
on gas. NGC emphasised, however, that some of the planned stations could be
cancelled. Half will be built by small private-sector generating companies
that have emerged since the electricity industry was privatised two years
ago. The remainder will be built by National Power and PowerGen, the two big
generators created at privatisation. Their construction is controversial
because British Coal, National Power and PowerGen think many will be more
expensive than existing coal-fired plant and should not be built. They
believe the new gas stations will survive only because they have managed to
sign contracts to sell power to regional electricity companies at what will
prove to be above market prices. That means they will take market share from
National Power and PowerGen's older stations, although those may actually be
generating cheaper power.
Most vulnerable are smaller coal and oil-fired stations, such as National
Power's Padiham, Willington, Uskmouth and Staythorpe stations, and
PowerGen's High Marnham and Drakelow B stations. National Power said it
would fight to keep good coal stations open. Nuclear Electric is on course
for another profitable year, Mr John Collier, the company's chairman, said
yesterday. Results for the financial year just ended, which will be
announced in July, would be 'very rosy indeed'.
The state-owned company, which owns and operates the nuclear power stations
of England and Wales, produced a record amount of electricity in the year to
last month, Mr Collier said. It generated 45,000 megawatt-hours of
electricity, compared with 42 the previous year. Offer, the electricity
industry watchdog, yesterday amended the market rules to allow more
companies to choose their electricity supplier, rather than having to buy
from their local company.
The rules allowed only companies buying more than 1MW to choose their
supplier. The amendment enables companies that are subsidiaries of the same
group and occupy the same site to add together their purchases to push them
over the 1MW limit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
