<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / Market forces curb audit fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDIT FEES are falling back towards levels of two years ago, a study
indicated yesterday.
Bills for 42 quoted companies with year-ends on or after December 1991 have
dropped 2.7 per cent to Pounds 53.7m, according to JDH Consultants, the
Glasgow-based firm.
That compares with a rise in audit bills for the same companies of 5 per
cent to Pounds 55.2m last year, up from Pounds 52.6m in the previous 12
months.
The study, which used figures from the annual reports of companies that have
reported so far this year, provides evidence of the competition between
accountancy firms.
It comes as companies are increasingly putting their audits out to tender -
or threatening to do so - in an attempt to cut costs in the face of the
recession.
The trend is depressing news for the accountancy firms, which traditionally
rely on audit fees during a downturn, when income from other sources such as
corporate finance and management consultancy declines.
Mr Dennis Henry, JDH managing director, said: 'This study emphasis the fact
that auditors are not escaping the pressures placed on their clients.'
The largest declines include a 46 per cent fall at Alfred McAlpine from
Pounds 565,000 to Pounds 305,000 - which changed auditor from Touche Ross to
Price Waterhouse - and 44 per cent from Pounds 1.6m to Pounds 900,000 for
English China Clay, audited by KPMG Peat Marwick.
The highest fee in the study is from BTR, the industrial group, audited by
Ernst &amp; Young, which has remained static at Pounds 7m for the past three
years.
Report on audit fees of UK public companies. JDH Consultants, 11 Clydebrae
Drive, Bothwell, Glasgow G71 8SB. Pounds 250.
</TEXT>
