<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / First shots fired in council elections: Tories stress
prudence - Labour fears for democracy / MPs worried about poor interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOTH MAIN parties launched their local government elections campaigns
yesterday with the Tories emphasising authorities as 'enablers' rather than
providers of services. Labour responded with a warning that local democracy
was threatened.
Both main parties were united in asserting that they were confident of
running vigorous campaigns, although the elections follow so soon after a
fiercely fought general poll.
Privately, however, MPs in both parties admit that motivating not only their
supporters but also the electorate is likely to be difficult.
The elections, on May 7, are taking place for all seats in the 53 district
councils in Scotland and for a third of seats in 155 of the district
councils in England and Wales. There are no elections in London or for
county councils.
Launching the campaign, Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, and Mr
John Redwood, the local-government minister, said that only the Tories could
stop councils being 'captured by service providers' and achieve services
local communities wanted at prices they could afford.
Labour, Mr Howard added, was 'in no position' to claim any interest in the
quality of services, as the party's leading figures were 'grubbing around
for the votes of public-service unions' in the leadership election.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, rejected the charge and said
that the government's drive towards centralisation and privatisation in
local services would intensify. In the campaign, Labour plans to emphasises
the role of local councils as a check on central government.
Producing illustrative figures for the council tax, which will replace the
poll tax next year, Mr Gould warned that the new system would mean people in
the south facing higher bills than under the poll tax.
Both Labour and the Tories emphasised that in some cases only a handful of
votes could change the political control of a council. Mr Chris Patten, the
Tory party chairman, said the party would be looking for some gains in
controlling councils rather than at a particular total for the number of
seats overall. Mr John Cunningham, Labour's campaigns co-ordinator,
underlined the objective of consolidating a strong position from when those
seats were last contested in 1988.
In terms of gains, Labour will be looking to areas where it did well in
parliamentary seats. The Tories pointed out that in some places where the
Liberal Democrats had failed to take long-standing target seats in the
Westminster elections, their local authority base might be more vulnerable
than before.
</TEXT>
