<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / Treasury shuffles the regulation pack: The implications of
changing the ministry responsible for policing financial services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOVING ministerial responsibility for the regulation of financial services
sounds simple enough. Shifting 50 people and their filing cabinets across
Parliament Square from the Department of Trade and Industry to the Treasury
is not one of the biggest departmental reshuffles of recent years - but its
long-term effects might be far-reaching.
The announcement of the switch earlier this month threw a series of
questions into the air like a pack of cards. The answers will determine how
London's financial markets are regulated and how some of its biggest
financial institutions are structured.
Will the Bank of England take a more direct role in overseeing the City's
investment markets? Will the Securities and Investments Board be left to
wither away, or will it be beefed up to become a UK version of the
Securities and Exchange Commission in the US?
Will London move further towards the sort of universal banking culture that
already dominates on the Continent?
The City has so far been given no clues to the answers - indeed, there is a
widespread view that Treasury ministers have yet to think through the
implications of the switch, foreshadowed in the Tory manifesto and due to
take place at the start of June. Both the Bank of England and the SIB say
they have been given no clear idea of what changes are planned, if any.
One City regulator commented yesterday: 'It really all boils down to what's
in ministers' minds. I'm not sure they are sure themselves yet.' According
to another, the Treasury is already discovering that the questions raised by
the switch are more complex than it had imagined.
Mr Robin Hutton, director of the British Merchant Banking and Securities
Houses Association, said: 'It's very early days yet, so we're trying to be
tolerant.'
One of the biggest effects of the move will to be bring together, under the
Treasury, two very different methods of overseeing wholesale financial
markets. London's short-term money markets, and those for foreign exchange,
gilts (government securities) and bullion come under the control of the Bank
of England. For those responsibilities the Bank has a loose informal
relationship with the Treasury.
The Bank's control of the markets is firm but informal. For instance,
participants in the money market have to comply with the Bank's
non-statutory code of conduct. Repeated failures would result in a firm
being struck off the Bank's recognised list, removing its exemption from the
Financial Services Act.
On the other hand, the wholesale investment markets, such as the stock and
bond markets, are governed by a rigid statutory framework with clear formal
reporting lines. The SIB, created by the 1986 Financial Services Act,
reports directly to ministers.
The two different approaches may not last. The Bank already has informal
involvement in the operation of the stock and bond markets.
Also, investment regulators have been striving for the past three years to
reduce the rigidity introduced to wholesale markets by the Financial
Services Act, in an effort to rekindle a more traditional informal
regulatory style well known to the Bank.
The switch of responsibility to the Treasury has now fuelled a strong belief
among some regulators that the Bank will eventually become more directly
involved in overseeing all London wholesale markets.
The Bank might also take on greater responsibility for overseeing London's
securities firms. Historically, the UK securities industry has operated
under different rules and regulations from the banking industry, a
distinction that was not removed after London's Big Bang, when commercial
banks were allowed to buy stockbrokers for the first time.
The Bank, as 'lead regulator', remains ultimately responsible for brokers
owned by banking groups. Also, proposed European legislation on the capital
backing needed by broking firms might eventually encourage more banks in
London to scrap broking subsidiaries and conduct securities business off
their balance sheets.
Under former corporate affairs minister Mr John Redwood, the DTI fought hard
to prevent European legislation that could undermine the structure of the
UK's securities industry, replacing it with a Continental-style universal
banking culture. Whether the Treasury will fight as hard has yet to be seen.
If the Bank of England's future role is open to question, then so is the
SIB's. This investment watchdog has always sat uncomfortably between
government and the investment industry, looking to the industry to pay the
costs of its upkeep but remaining answerable to ministers.
A change of political master could upset that delicate balance -
particularly if the Bank of England encroaches further on SIB territory.
Much depends on Mr Anthony Nelson, the new economic secretary at the
Treasury, who will take on responsibility for financial regulation. He is
seen in the City as a fan of the SIB, having personally introduced the
amendments to the Financial Services Act, which created the body.
One former DTI official involved in the passage of the act commented: 'He
kept pushing for more powers to be given to the SIB. He wanted things to be
centralised, and was a great critic of the City 'club'.' That aim seems to
have lain behind a clause which he tabled which gave SIB the power to make
rules directly on behalf of self-regulating organisations if it felt fit.
Mr Nelson might be the man to do what a growing number of people are arguing
for: to centralise the assorted investigatory powers that currently leave a
raft of self-regulating organisations, government officials and police all
pursuing the same fraud investigations. The SIB would then come to look far
more like the US Securities and Exchange Commission.
Under current plans, though, the DTI will remain responsible for carrying
out company and insider-dealing investigations. The complex web of
regulatory relationships that has grown up in the City is unlikely to be
swept away overnight.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
