<TEXT>
ANTI-RIOT police dispersed about 1,000 demonstrators in central Taipei at
dawn today, ending a five-day street protest mounted to demand democratic
reform, Reuter reports from Taipei.
Thousands of helmeted police, wielding clubs and firing water cannon,
dragged the protesters out of a makeshift camp built by the opposition
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) outside the capital's main railway
station.
Police punched and kicked the demonstrators, some of whom resisted and were
injured, witnesses said. The protesters were released several blocks away.
The DPP had occupied the street outside the station since Monday in a
demonstration to demand direct presidential elections.
