<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / BAe appoints ex-BTR chief as chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE ended its seven-month search for a chairman with
yesterday's announcement that Mr John Cahill, former chief executive of BTR,
will take over from Sir Graham Day next month.
Sir Graham has been acting chairman of BAe since Professor Sir Roland Smith
was forced to resign in a spectacular boardroom coup last September after
the failure of the company's Pounds 432m rights issue.
Other possible candidates are believed to have been approached but to have
been reluctant to take the job because they would have had to continue
working with BAe's existing top management team.
Sir Graham insisted that 'only one offer was made; John was the man. We are
very pleased'.
Mr Cahill said that he intended to work closely with Mr Dick Evans, BAe's
chief executive, and the company's board, but he would not be drawn on how
he planned to tackle the specific problems and issues facing the company.
Sir Graham said Mr Cahill would be a full-time chairman because 'you can't
do this job as a part-time chairman'.
Mr Cahill's immediate challenge will be to restore the credibility and
reputation of the company which was badly dented by the failure of its
rights issue, the ensuing boardroom turmoil and the resignation of Sir
Roland.
BAe's new chairman takes over as the company is refocusing on core defence
and aerospace businesses, under pressure because of defence cuts and the
slump in civil aviation. Mr Cahill regards defence 'as the main thrust' of
the company. 'We have an opportunity to pick up some market share in this
business,' he said, adding that he considered defence and aerospace as a
'healthy business'.
BAe will also announce the appointment of a finance director to replace Mr
Dudley Eustace, who resigned last month, at its annual shareholder's meeting
next Thursday.
The City welcomed the appointment of Mr Cahill, 62, an experienced
international businessman who was chief executive of the BTR industrial
engineering group from 1987 to 1991. BAe's shares closed yesterday 5p higher
at 348p after rising at one stage by as much as 16p.
After a review of BAe's activities, aerospace analysts expect Mr Cahill to
speed up the restructuring process spelt out in last year's rights issue
document.
Mr Cahill will work closely with Mr Evans and the present BAe senior
management, but is also expected to adopt a hands-on approach, examining
every business in BAe's portfolio.
'He is no soft touch, and he has a big opportunity to turn the company
around during the next five years,' one City analyst said.
Sir Graham said the search for a new chairman had involved finding 'someone
who was British with a solid business record and with international
experience'.
Observer, Page 17
Lex, Page 18
London stocks, Page 38
