<DOCNO>FT922-11585</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAEOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (26): Risk in a warm
climate - Geographical specialists / Investment trusts offer the only
practicable way to invest in underdeveloped markets on the periphery of
areas which currently have strong economies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOBODY IS suggesting that you should put all your life savings into the
Foreign &amp; Colonial Latin American Investment Trust.
Even the fund's own managers are quite happy to admit that that would be too
risky.
But if you had put some 'risk' money (ie, funds you were prepared to lose)
into it at end of last January, it would have done very nicely - the trust
rose 120 per cent over the next 12 months, according to Micropal, to make it
the most successful of all investment trusts over the time period.
It would be unwise to be seduced by investment performance over such a short
period, and the fund has not yet been going long enough to provide a
definitive record. But numbers like that command attention.
Latin America has been the star performer of late. But other areas ripe for
the specialist treatment include the Pacific Basin, and southern and eastern
Europe. All have underdeveloped markets, but stand on the periphery of areas
with currently strong economies.
If you want to cash in, investment trusts offer virtually the only
practicable vehicle. Illiquidity makes 'open-ended' funds such as unit
trusts inappropriate, because the size of the fund is allowed to fluctuate
in accordance with payments and withdrawals by investors. Heavy redemptions
could make life impossible for the fund manager, if it is difficult to find
buyers for large blocks of funds.
The strictures of regulators mean that many of these funds stay 'offshore',
rather than tempt too many novice investors into risky investment waters.
Managers that specialise in exotic narrowly based funds include:
Tyndall, whose stable includes First Philippine and Korea Liberalisation;
Lloyds Bank, which offers the First Spanish and the German investment
trusts; and
John Govett, which offers a whole array, mostly based offshore, such as
Mexican Horizons, Malaysian Emerging, Singapore SESDAQ and the Hungarian
Investment Company.
The companies take differing attitudes to the marketing of the products.
John Govett regards its funds, which tend to invest in highly illiquid
markets, as being for institutional use. Richard Royds, managing director,
points out that the minimum investment in its ground-breaking Hungarian
trust at launch was Pounds 25,000, while the average size of deals since has
been Pounds 20,000 - not within reach of the 'small' investor.
Govett's aim is to allow pension funds and other institutional investors the
chance of exposure to markets with particular growth opportunities. However,
it hopes in time to offer the funds to the mass market. Tyndall takes a
similar line.
F&amp;C, unlike Govett, offers a regular savings scheme for investors in both
its Latin American and German investment trusts. Audley Twiston Davies, who
manages the Latin American fund, remains bullish about future prospects for
the region, and sees the area as offering a broad investment spread. For
example, the trust has recently taken on its first exposure to Peru, and
plans to move into Ecuador.
He points out that growth for the next 10 years is forecast at an annual 5
per cent, by the International Monetary Fund, and he sees other moderately
defensive qualities. 'In Latin America, you have a nice mix of economies
which have substantially gone through a restructuring process. You can start
to value them more like a mainstream stock market. And they don't look too
expensive.'
It should be obvious to any reasonably sensible investor that the investment
story for these markets in itself makes the potential risks and
opportunities greater than they might otherwise be. But the extra risks
bequeathed by the technical factors which determine investment trust pricing
might be more awkward to detect.
Most investment trusts trade at a discount to their net asset value, which
is largely fuelled by market sentiment. Sudden events which rocked
confidence in a specific geographical area could be disastrous for the value
of shares in a geographically specialist investment trust.
More awkward still, some of these trusts even stand at a premium. This tends
to amplify further the risks and opportunities associated with the trusts.
Robin Angus, investment trust analyst at County Nat West, puts it this way:
'Of course, there's much more volatility with a geographically specialist
trust. Naturally the trust is more likely to move to a discount or a
premium, because you have not got checks and balances within your
portfolio.'
He points out that exceptions can be made for trusts specialising in the UK,
as this tends to be the home for UK money; and also for trusts such as
Fleming Overseas, which specialise in overseas investment but give
themselves a broader spread.
But Bruce Ackerman, a director of several Lloyds Bank investment trusts,
points out that, while markets are difficult to enter, institutional
interest will remain high: 'There is a high correlation between small
discounts and the closedness of the market to outside investment.'
Once the markets open up more, institutions might even lose interest because
they can invest direct. He is therefore less nervous than Mr Angus about the
volatility of share prices compared with net asset value.
Also, discount volatility can always work in the investor's favour, if
shares move to a premium from a discount. But Mr Angus' view is still clear:
'I would never advise any individual to put more than a small punt on a
specialist trust. If you want to back a hunch, that's fine, provided you've
got maybe 10 times that much in one of the big broadly spread trusts.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-11586</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAENFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (25): Raised ceiling
clears the air - Personal equity plans / Abolition of the Pounds 3,000 limit
has simplified tax-free investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INVESTMENT trust sector succeeded in getting most of what it wanted with
Norman Lamont's Budget. The Pounds 3,000 limit on an investment or unit
trust in a personal equity plan was abolished in favour of the full Pounds
6,000 allowance.
Shares held in a Pep are free of income and capital gains tax. The industry
had been lobbying hard for a 'level playing field' with direct equity
investment.
The Pounds 3,000 ceiling on collective funds had arguably worked against the
interests of the private investor and against the government's own policy of
encouraging wider share ownership. It meant that private investors were
exposed to the performance of a handful of Peppable shares, instead of being
able to spread their holdings in collective funds.
The Association of Investment Trust Companies welcomed the change in the
Budget, and said it hoped that it would encourage investment trusts to
launch more Peps.
The abolition of the Pounds 3,000 band simplifies the Pep structure for
investment trusts. There are now only two levels for investment through a
Pep - the maximum Pounds 6,000 and Pounds 1,500. What the investment trust
industry was hoping for, but did not get, was the abolition of this lower
limit, which applies to 'non-qualifying' trusts.
A trust must hold at least half its funds in shares in the UK or another EC
member state in order to qualify under the Pep regulations. Of the 250 or so
investment trusts on the market, only 96 currently qualify under the Pep
rules.
The category most affected by Mr Lamont's decision not to abolish the Pounds
1,500 level, apart from the investment trusts which invest specifically in
areas outside the EC, is the large international general trusts. These
invest in different markets worldwide, lessening the private investor's
exposure to a single market. 'The big general international trusts are still
excluded, yet they are the ideal place for the first-time investor,' said
the AITC.
Six of the eight trusts managed by Foreign &amp; Colonial are 'non-qualifying',
including its general international fund, the largest investment trust. This
has about 50 per cent of its assets in the UK and the EC; but to qualify, it
would have to commit itself to raise this to about 55 per cent in case it
needed to sell stock in one of these markets.
'The whole thing is a nonsense,' said Jeremy Tigue, of Foreign &amp; Colonial.
'It's a crazy distinction to make. Our good results have been due to our
flexibility.'
Foreign &amp; Colonial started to offer Peps last October and has sold 3,500 so
far. Only two funds - the Eurotrust and German investment trusts - are
qualifying. F&amp;C 'tops up' its Pep to Pounds 6,000 with the others by adding
blue-chip shares - BT, BTR, BAT, Lloyds Bank and Shell - to cover the
remainder.
Mr Tigue estimates that, as a result of the non-qualifying rule, F&amp;C loses
out by Pounds 4,500 for each Pep sold - a total of Pounds 15.6m. He says
that F&amp;C, while reluctant to become a qualifying trust, is leaving its
options open.
But the abolition of the Pounds 3,000 Pep ceiling will put more pressure on
the non-qualifying trusts, believes Hamish Buchan, head of investment trust
research at County NatWest WoodMac. 'It suddenly opens up the gap between
the qualifying and non-qualifying trusts,' he says. 'Those such as Foreign &amp;
Colonial and Alliance may find themselves at a competitive disadvantage as a
result.'
However, the industry as a whole can only benefit from the abolition of the
Pounds 3,000 ceiling. In 1991-92 investment trusts concentrated on new
issues, to take advantage of the loophole in the Pep rules that allowed such
trusts to qualify for the Pounds 6,000 limit.
M&amp;G launched two new issues - Income and Recovery - and there were many
other issues from managers such as Fidelity and Robert Fleming.
Many such issues had split-capital structures, and a high income, offering
particular attractions to a Pep investor. For example, M&amp;G Income offered a
6.55 per cent yield, equivalent to 11 per cent gross for a higher-rate
taxpayer.
Split-capital issues also helped prevent the shares dropping to a discount
to net assets on trading, a problem with investment trust new issues. But
now that it is possible to put a full Pounds 6,000 into an existing trust,
investors can buy assets at a discount.
New issues may well be squeezed out of the Pep market as a result of the
abolition of the Pounds 3,000 ceiling, and unit trusts, with their freedom
to advertise, may once more take the lion's share of the Pep market.
Of the Pounds 4.5bn invested in Peps in the year to April 1991, only Pounds
180m went into investment trust Peps, compared with Pounds 1.44bn in unit
trusts. Unit trusts can usually afford to spend more on promotion, because
of their higher charges, while investment trusts are quoted companies and
therefore are not allowed to advertise their shares. (However, this
restriction does not apply to their savings plans.)
With the uncertainty of the election out of the way, the future of Peps
looks secure and investors can expect an increased number of investment
trusts to offer Peps.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
