<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (22): Back to rejoin
the mainstream - In spite of problems brought by the recession, investment
trust professionals believe the sector is returning to its roots as a
vehicle for small investors to enter the equity market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTMENT TRUSTS have been enjoying a revival. After years of being the
poor relations of the fund management industry, they were flavour of the
moment for much of the 1991-92 tax year.
There were two reasons. The first was personal equity plans. Whereas unit
trust Peps were limited to Pounds 3,000 in 1991-92, an investment trust new
issue qualified for a full Pounds 6,000 Pep.
The result was a proliferation of investment trust launches with a
'tax-free' label, notably the Pounds 246m raised by M&amp;G's Income trust.
Norman Lamont may have put a stop to this trend, by allowing all unit and
investment trusts with 50 per cent of assets in the EC to qualify for the
Pounds 6,000 limit. It will now make more sense to put Pounds 6,000 into an
existing trust - and acquire assets at a discount - than to invest in a new
trust and pay a premium for assets (after issue expenses).
The second boost to investment trusts has been the decision of some to pay
commission, which has attracted independent financial advisers who had not
previously recommended investment trusts.
The change casts doubt on the notion that consumers receive 'best advice'.
How can it be best advice to recommend investment trusts with a 3 per cent
upfront charge, when it was not best advice to recommend trusts when they
carried no charge at all?
To be fair, advisers have also been attracted to trusts by the revival of
split-capital structures, which have made investment trust shares highly
flexible tools for private investors.
Income shares, in particular, when placed in a Pep, can offer double-digit
tax-free yields. Zero-coupon shares offer steady capital growth, which gives
investors an efficient way of using up their capital gains tax allowance.
Capital shares are a vehicle for those who want to speculate on a quick rise
in the market.
But there are dangers in these structures. To date, the gains have been made
by the zero and income shareholders, with the capital shares tending to
drift down in the absence of a bull market.
One must also question whether all those who have bought income shares have
known exactly what they have been buying. In some cases, income shares are
deliberately designed as an 'annuity'. They will have virtually no capital
value on wind-up. Investors may be delighted with the high yields on offer,
but how many of them realise that a good chunk of the income is simply the
return of their capital?
Other structures have zero shares attached to so-called 'ordinary income'
shares. The latter get all the income of the trust but will only be repaid
after the claims of the zero holders have been met. If equity returns are
low in the 1990s (and some believe this will be the case), the remorseless
upward growth in the zeros may eat away at the redemption value of the
ordinary income shares.
And even the zeros are not guaranteed to be redeemed at full value. A
collapse in the stock market at the wrong moment might hit a trust's ability
to repay the zeros, and cause a nasty shock to those who thought they had
acquired 'safe' investments.
New private investor recruits to the sector may also be disillusioned if a
combination of falling stock markets and widening discounts creates
substantial plunges in trust share prices. Such losses could easily wipe out
the tax privileges available to Pep holders.
One need only look at the losses incurred by shareholders in some of those
trusts which have large unquoted holdings in their portfolios, as asset
values have dropped and discounts have widened in the recession.
Despite these potential problems, most investment trust professionals are
delighted that the sector is returning to its roots - of being a vehicle for
small investors to enter the equity market. The launch of trusts by groups
such as M&amp;G and Fidelity will have widened the market, according to Paul
Manduca, chairman of the Association of Investment Trust Companies.
Investment trusts still have an important role to play in specialist
geographical markets. Institutions are still prepared to sub-contract
investment management in areas such as south-east Asia and Latin America,
and for private investors, a collective fund is the only practicable means
of access to such markets.
The challenge for the 1990s is to maintain the momentum - to prevent the
cycle of over-supply of trusts, widening discounts and predatory action
which shrinks the sector. There are still predators around. Despite the
general narrowing of discounts, a number of trusts have been taken over or
reconstructed, notably Govett Atlantic. If managers slip in performance,
they will need to keep an eye on their share registers.
A further battle may be needed to allow international generalist trusts,
such as Foreign &amp; Colonial, to qualify for the full Pep allowance. At
present, unless such trusts commit themselves to keep more than 50 per cent
of their assets in the EC, their Pep allowance is just Pounds 1,500. This
dissuades private investors from backing what are acknowledged to be good
first-time investment vehicles.
There will certainly be intense competition for private investors' cash in
the 1990s. The advantages of unit trusts, which were struggling to compete
in 1991-92, may be rediscovered. Now that investment trusts are paying
commission, they have lost some of their cost advantage over their unitised
rivals, especially if other unit trusts follow the lead of Murray Johnstone
and reduce their front-end fees.
The narrowing of discounts, which boosted the relative performance of
investment trusts vis-a-vis unit trusts in the late 1980s, will not be
repeated in the early 1990s.
But at least investment trusts, after years of being in the backwaters of
the financial services industry, are back in the mainstream.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
