<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (21): 'No results,
no fee' for the investors' first-aider - Hindsight / Too many Fimbra members
give bad advice, claims Toby Micklethwait, whose organisation tries to help
savers who have lost money to pursue compensation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOBY MICKLETHWAIT's life changed when a friend of his lost Pounds 50,000
through dealing with a Fimbra member.
Fimbra is the acronym for Financial Intermediaries, Managers and Brokers
Regulatory Association - the regulatory body for independent financial
advisers.
A chartered accountant, who had been a finance director in business, Mr
Micklethwait set about trying to obtain compensation for his friend.
That led to the formation of the Association of Investors, a loose
organisation which consists of professionals who are engaged in trying to
help those fighting for compensation from the financial services industry,
and the team leaders of groups of investors who have lost money.
'Our aims,' says Mr Micklethwait, 'are to see the quality of advice improve
dramatically, and not be wrongly motivated; to ensure that compensation
system operates quickly and fairly; and to see a reduction in the quantity
of thefts.'
Those who attended the association's first conference, in October 1991,
included solicitors Alexander Tatham, Hewson Clark, Hodkinsons and J Keith
Park; also the Consumers' Association, Age Concern, the Association of
Lloyds Names, and Paul Cooper, a financial journalist who campaigns in this
field.
To earn a living, Mr Micklethwait asks for a percentage of the compensation
received, and works on a 'no-results, no-fee' basis, rather like an American
lawyer. The fee can vary between 10 and 30 per cent, depending on the
prospects of achieving success.
However, he says: 'This is not a race in which it is particularly pleasant
to be the leader. Cash flow is a problem. It can take years to get a
result.'
A further difficulty can occur after compensation has been secured.
Investors who readily agreed to pay a percentage when hope of compensation
seemed small, may then turn round and say with hindsight: 'It wasn't so
difficult.'
Nevertheless, Mr Micklethwait says he believes that contingent fees are very
advantageous. 'Many of these people have no money for legal fees, and cannot
get legal aid,' he says.
Questioned about how future problems for investors can be avoided, he is
forthright: 'Fimbra is a very bad profession. There are no proper entry
controls; no exams; anyone can become a member. It is very slow to throw
people out. Far too many Fimbra members give very bad advice.'
Most advisers are paid by the commission system, under which insurance
companies reward intermediaries through a percentage of the premiums paid by
the consumer. Mr Micklethwait thinks this system is unacceptable.
'Good advice does not mix with commission being paid by the supplier of the
product.' he says. 'We must stop Fimbra members taking commission.
'We need a huge publicity campaign to make people very uncomfortable with
the concept of free advice. SIB (the Securities and Investments Board),
rather than sitting helplessly, could ask for money to mount a campaign.
Fimbra and Lautro are not going to stop commissions on their own.'
He doubts the efficacy of the various warning notes which regulators have
placed in documentation. 'People can't go through life reading the small
print.'
The alternative system to commission is for the consumer to pay a fee to the
adviser direct, based normally on an hourly rate for work done. Many
advisers say that they cannot persuade consumers to pay a fee, and that they
would go out of business without commissions.
'I don't care,' says Mr Micklethwait. 'It seems to me that accountants can
handle the whole business of financial advice; they have exams and strict
entry procedures.'
What has the association achieved though its campaigning? Mr Micklethwait
claims some successes, such as the Dale Greaves investors who had bought
fake bonds. Many, but not all, have now been paid compensation. His original
friend now has a fighting chance of repayment; the Fimbra member has been
declared in default, the first step towards obtaining compensation.
Another achievement is that a number of campaigners, including Mr
Micklethwait, have succeeded in getting Aylesbury Associates declared in
default. Aylesbury was one of many companies selling home-income plans,
which have proved the bane of many elderly investors.
The aim of these plans was to unlock the capital tied up in the homes of old
people. The biggest problems have arisen with schemes which involved
insurance bonds. In essence, the schemes involved the investors remortgaging
their houses and using the proceeds of the loan to buy a bond. That bond was
supposed to provide them with enough income to meet the interest payments
and with further income on top. Rising house prices would, meanwhile, reduce
the significance of the mortgage.
Instead, the values of the bonds and of the houses fell. Interest rates rose
and the income from the bonds could not keep up. The investors found their
position steadily worsening, with the mortgage assuming a greater and
greater proportion of their homes' value.
Mr Micklethwait thinks that nearly all those who have been involved in what
he calls 'home gambling' schemes will have to sell their homes. Half of
those who entered an Aylesbury scheme already had a mortgage - that alone,
says Mr Micklethwait, scuppers their financial positions.
Many of those people who were involved in home-income plans are still
fighting for compensation, and a number of victim support groups have been
established.
Although he says he obviously has a conflict of interest, Mr Micklethwait
feels that those pursuing claims against financial companies should sign up
with professionals such as himself. Clients need a great deal of help on day
one, he says: often they have not heard of the investors' compensation
scheme.
Contact names and numbers for those who feel they have a claim: Toby
Micklethwait, Association of Investors, 0932 873557; Anthony Gold, of
solicitors Alexander Tatham, 061 236-4444; Paul Stafford, of solicitors
Harrison Clark, 0905 612001; Neil Stevens, of solicitors Trethowan, 0722
412299. Paul Cooper, journalist, runs an advice business called Claims (081
947 6046). Hillary Morgan, of Aylesbury Victims Support Group, 0732 61704;
Marjorie Gumbley, of East Kent Home Income Scheme Action Group, 0304 372835;
Peter Dawson, of Gloucestershire Home Income Scheme Action Group, 0285
740527.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
