<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (20): An evergreen
chartist with an eye for healthy growth - Serious riches / Christmas is a
year-round business for John St George Syms, who runs the family tree
plantation.  And so, too, is investment - mainly in equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHRISTMAS does not necessarily come only once a year
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
it's a year-round business for Mr John St George Syms.
Mr Syms, a 79-year-old, who spent his career balancing the very different
pressures of the Bar and a country farm, is also a founder of the UK
Christmas Tree Growers Association, and its second chairman.
He provides the Christmas tree for Number 10, Downing Street each year.
Initially, he had hoped to set up a competition, modelled on a similar
scheme in the US where different growers compete to provide the White House
tree. But now Mr Syms he finds that his peers are happy to leave the
responsibility to him, so it has become an annual job.
As the photograph on this page, taken last month, confirms, shows, Christmas
trees grow around the year, and Mr Syms still pays there is still close
attention to his plantation, situated on the edge of the estate, to the
south of London.
This estate has itself been the subject of a number of legal transactions,
starting in 1967. Mr Syms passed the estate on to his son by his first wife
(he is now married for the second time). This was not as radical a measure
as it sounds, because he has retained a life interest - 'He can't get rid of
me until I'm 92, so I'm pretty secure.'
In many ways, Mr Syms' his life has revolved around the family estate, which
his father bought in 1921. He bought the neighbouring estate, twice as large
as the estate he inherited, in 1953, and it has since grown more or less in
his own image. Thus there are fishing lakes (which several years ago he sold
to his son) and also the Christmas trees.
This business grew up almost by accident. Mr Syms' father started the
plantation fairly unscientifically. Then a traveller asked to buy some trees
for Christmas. One of his father's clients, an American businessman, then
gave him some advice that he has never forgotten: 'When you grow older, you
will realise it will pay you to employ someone else to do that work you are
doing.'
The business is still growing, and an extra five to ten acres is planted
each year. Tending the plantation is a full-time job, now in the hands of Mr
Syms' son, Mark.
Investment is, similarly, a year-round job requiring diligent attention.
While Mr Syms has always enlisted the advice of brokers, he also leans
heavily on investment research.
In his own words, he is an avowed chartist. The particular charts that he
has consulted for more than two decades now are produced by Investment
Research, of Cambridge. They indicate the performance of both general
sectors and specific shares relative to their appropriate index.
For a chart to tell Mr Syms to buy, in broad terms, it needs to have started
to outperform its index. Wait too long and the opportunity may be lost, he
believes.
Having consulted the runes of the chart, Mr Syms will pick up the phone and
consult his stockbroker, who is Neil Pedley, of James Capel.
This is an 'advisory' relationship, which means that Mr Pedley is within his
rights to try to argue Mr Syms out of a stock selection. He can also
telephone with good ideas of his own. But he does not have discretion to
make transactions unless specifically authorised.
However, it is a mark of the respect between the two men that Mr Pedley does
have discretion to make sales when he sees fit, and to give advice.
'When the crash came in 1987, I bailed out of everything,' recalls Mr Syms.
'I'm not saying I was right. Then, after two years, I decided it was time I
got reinvested again.'
He spent a year in gilts during 1989, and then took the decision to buy
shares again. By now, he was out of contact with the City, so he turned for
advice to his accountant, who recommended Mr Pedley.
'We don't have a stereotyped arrangement,' explains Mr Syms. 'I subscribe to
Investment Research, so every now and then, if I see something I like, I
tell him to buy it. We talk on the telephone about two or three times a
week.'
Equities now make up 90 per cent of his portfolio, with 10 per cent in cash.
He no longer holds any gilts.
This tends to suggest that age has not coloured his investment outlook with
too much conservatism. A look through the individual shares in his portfolio
further bears this out. For example, one of his strongest performers is
Eurodisney.
However, the bedrock of the portfolio is in solid stocks. 'I would say about
50 per cent of my stocks are in the FT-SE 100. I try to avoid speculation.'
If he does want to speculate, he uses traded options.
While Mr Syms' standard holding in a company is Pounds 7,500, he only risks
Pounds 1,500 when putting money into options. He had already developed a
taste for this form of investment from previous successful forays into
commodity futures.
One of his most recent choices shows a gambler's instinct, both for making
the right choice and for quitting while he was ahead. He bought a call
option in Midland Bank for June. This was an execution-only deal  - Mr
Pedley could not advise him on it, because James Capel is owned By Hongkong
&amp; Shanghai Bank. As Mr Syms puts it:
'For a period of time, it was 50 per cent down. Then I checked, and it had
had an enormous rise. I rang up and said to take the profit once it had
doubled. I think the thing's gone up more since.'
The principle, of course, is to take your winnings while you are ahead. This
was before the takeover of Midland by Hongkong &amp; Shanghai, which would
probably have helped increase the value of the option further.
This judicious mixture of strong investments, having made decisions based on
fundamentals, plus a sensible gambler's instinct for profit at the more
speculative margins, stems naturally from Mr Syms' upbringing.
He is a 'fifth generation' lawyer, the son of a solicitor. Following school
at Harrow, he went on to Magdalen College, Oxford, where he read history,
and thence to the Bar, where he specialised in divorce law.
At this time, as in childhood, his great interest was horse racing. It
remains so, and a painting of the racehorse Desert Orchid now adorns his
wall.
His experiences during the war may also have helped to sharpen his instinct
for shrewd investment: he was a gunner in Catalina flying-boats, and saw
service in the North Atlantic at the height of the U-boat war, and then in
India. The plane in which he was a crew member shadowed the Bismarck for
seven hours.
Mr Syms has another investment which at the moment might seem a little
risky: he is a Lloyd's Name. This is an investment he has maintained for 42
years, since first being introduced to a syndicate by a friend from Oxford.
This year, he incurred his first loss, and he is still more than satisfied
with the value the investment has offered over the long term.
He has short shrift for the Names currently serving Lloyd's with writs.
'I've got no sympathy with that at all.' However, he admits that many of the
newer Names have not had the chance to build up reserves as he has done.
But his defence of Lloyd's is resolute, and he remains greatly impressed by
the Task Force's report which was published in January.
He does not believe it has been dominated by insiders, but he adds: 'It is
absolutely wrong that if agents have been guilty of malpractices the
financial burden should fall on the Names.'
At the age of 79, could caution now be seeping into his investment
attitudes? Not a bit of it.
One of Mr Syms' latest investments is a greyhound called Miller's Crossing.
On February 5. it won the 9.00 at Wembley, netting Pounds 500 for its proud
owner.
Why buy a greyhound? Mr Syms' answer is simple: 'Because I couldn't afford
to buy a racehorse.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
