<DOCNO>FT922-11596</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAEDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (15): Few openings
if Bush loses - Most dealers expect the president to be re-elected in
October. But should defeat seem imminent, US markets would fall
significantly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GEORGE BUSH's mortality, both physical and political, was rammed home at the
end of last year by his bilious tour of Japan, and then in February by his
embarrassing showing in the New Hampshire primary.
Things look better for him now, but it still does not require too much
imagination to picture his losing the presidency in November.
Such a volcanic change of the political landscape seems certain to produce
shifts in the market. This could require changes, both in stock selection
and also at the level of international asset allocation.
But the investment professionals have not spotted many new opportunities. At
the moment, they are rather more worried by the damage a Bush defeat would
do. Despite his well publicised wobbles at the turn of the year, most
dealers believe that Mr Bush will win again, and US stocks are priced
accordingly.
Should it become obvious that the president was going to lose, US markets
would probably endure significant falls.
A Bush defeat would probably mean that the US economy would have fallen
below current expectations, and that recovery had not arrived on cue. This
would require cuts in share prices.
Wall Street would also perhaps react negatively to a Democrat president,
solely on grounds of sentiment. It is difficult to prove this with any
certainty, because Democratic victories are now so rare - the last was Jimmy
Carter's in 1976 - but Peter Oppenheimer, chief economic strategist at
Hambros Bank, has produced figures which suggest that the market is
politically sensitive.
The Dow-Jones index shows a detectable election cycle under both parties, in
which it rallies sharply in the last six months prior to the election, and
performs strongly in the third year of the political cycle (as indeed it did
last year).
However, according to Mr Oppenheimer, 1976 shows up as an exception to the
rule. In the six months prior to that election, US equities only rose 2.1
per cent, the lowest rise in any comparable period since 1968, and far lower
than the 21.3 per cent in the six months before Ronald Reagan's first
victory.
Markets also did worse in the first 12 months of Carter (down 11.4 per cent)
than at any other comparable point in the political cycle - in the first 12
months of George Bush, the S&amp;P Composite went forward 22.3 per cent,
according to Hambros.
These last figures catch the height of 'merger-mania', which was great for
stocks. This was closely associated with the Republicans, and a new
administration, with tighter controls over corporate activity, would close
off hopes of a return to the big leveraged deals.
In the long term, Chris Goudie, of Baring Investment Management, doubts
whether a Democrat administration would be so bad, but says the short-term
effect would be marked. This would make long-term bond yields more
attractive.
For international asset allocation, the tougher question concerns the
dollar. Dealers are unlikely to trust a Democrat administration, which would
put the dollar under pressure. This would be an argument for switching out
of US equities. However, Mr Goudie again tones down this risk. He suggests
that this would only be a marked effect if Democrats retained control of the
Senate, which some commentators believe they could lose in November.
The other risk concerns base rates, which many might expect to move up under
a Democratic administration. However, a political change seems unlikely to
affect this, as they are already thought to be at the bottom and set to rise
with growth in the economy, even if Bush does win.
A Bush defeat would, therefore, probably be bad news for US equities in the
short, and possibly the medium, term.
If asset allocation is hard to call, stock selection is even tougher. Here
are one or two of the experts' hunches:
Oil companies could be expected to do very badly, for several reasons.
First, the Democrats are thought to be much more likely to push through
tighter legislation against pollution.
Martin Brook, fund manager for Cannon Lincoln, points to the legislation
already enacted in California to force petrol providers to lay on special
pumps which cut down on emissions. These cost roughly Dollars 1,000 a pump.
It would be bad news for oil companies, and their share prices, if such
measures came into force across the US.
Second, the oil industry has always been regarded as a natural bedmate of
the Republican party. Loss of its privileged access to government would harm
sentiment towards it among traders.
Motor companies might also expect to be hit hard by environmentalist
legislation against 'gas guzzlers' requiring cars to have a certain minimum
number of miles per gallon.
It is doubtful, however, whether a Democrat president would do much to harm
the car industry, as it is likely he would have been elected with the help
of blue-collar votes from Michigan and the other auto-industry states.
Environmental protection companies ought, by the same token, to do better.
In the UK, Commercial Union has recently launched an international
investment trust to take advantage of investment opportunities that arise
from enacting new environmental legislation. It is skewed slightly towards
the US. Specialist niche companies, involved in purification, air filter
scrubbers or monitoring systems, which tend to trade globally, could all do
well.
Retailers might be helped, particularly those at the lower end of the
market. Michael Moule, of Touche Remnant, who manages the Bankers and Law
Debenture investment trusts, points out that companies such as K-mart and
Wal-mart might benefit from any extra spending power given to people in
lower earning brackets. Their lack of any international exposure would also
lead them to out-perform other stocks.
Health might be given a boost in confidence under the Democrats, so
companies operating in the sector could perform well.
It might not be wise to carry this argument too far, as these stocks have
already performed very well. For example, Framlington's health unit trust,
60 per cent of which was invested in US health stocks, rose 91 per cent last
year alone.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-11597</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAECFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (14): Takeover
sweetens the holding - The Taveners deal sees the investment up by 24.6% in
six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GOLDSTEIN-JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE autumn Quarterly Review, I selected shares in the sweet
manufacturers, Taveners, for the portfolio.
I believed that this small company had take-over potential, because it had
attractive products, produced reasonable profits, and already had a
shareholder, Finnish confectionery group Karl Fazer, with a 29.89 per cent
stake in the company.
The portfolio bought 3,500 Taveners shares, paying 70p each.
In February, Taveners announced an agreed takeover by Toms Fabrikker, a
Danish chocolate and confectionery group. The portfolio accepted the
takeover terms of 165p per share. In addition, Taveners paid a special
dividend of 6p per share. Thus, an investment costing Pounds 2,450 in
October produced cash of Pounds 5,985 in March. What is especially nice
about accepting a cash takeover bid is that shares can be disposed of
without incurring any dealing charges.
Together with accrued interest on its earlier cash holding in the Britannia
Building Society, this brings the portfolio's cash holdings to Pounds 7,514.
This means the portfolio is up a very healthy 24.6 per cent in six months.
There is a tremendous temptation, when holding so much cash and having made
a modest stock market 'killing', immediately to plunge back into the market
and hope to repeat the performance of the Taveners investment.
However, the portfolio's other main investment - shares in Gestetner, also
bought in October last year - serves as a sharp warning that what goes up
can also go dramatically down. In these uncertain times for world stock
markets, cash does have some advantages.
The portfolio will continue to hold its Gestetner shares, although it will
now set a limit at which the shares will be sold. If Gestetner shares fall
below 90p and look as if they will fall further, then the portfolio will cut
its losses and dispose of them. If Gestetner then continues its share price
slide, the portfolio might consider buying back the shares if they were to
fall within the 60p to 65p range.
Taking a five-year view, I still feel that Gestetner should be a reasonable
investment, although recent profits performance has been poor. For example,
for the year to October 31, 1991, pre-tax profits fell by 57 per cent, from
Pounds 52.1m to Pounds 22.5m. However, the year-end gearing, counting its
outstanding loan stock as debt, was sharply reduced from 96 per cent to 26
per cent. The company has also shed more than 1,000 employees, about
one-tenth of its workforce.
It is also worth remembering that Ricoh, the Japanese office-equipment and
camera-maker, bought a 24.2 per cent stake in Gestetner in September last
year, paying 250p per share.
Ricoh's own business has been suffering recently. It has fallen into losses
for the first time since it was listed in 1949.
In March, it was reported that Mr Hiroshi Hamada, Ricoh's president, had
ordered all Ricoh directors to 'have a resignation letter in your shirt
pocket' every day at work, as a reminder that the resignations could be
accepted at any time if the company's performance did not improve.
It seems likely, therefore, that, if Gestetner does not improve its profits,
too, the Japanese may urge some strong action. Or perhaps they might sell
their stake in Gestetner to another possible predator or increase their
stake to gain control.
In any event, Gestetner remains an interesting, if risky, speculation. It
has a worldwide spread of interests, and, if the pound were ever devalued
(or 'realigned within the ERM'), this could help to boost the company's
overseas sales and profits.
Ricoh is one of the official sponsors of this year's Olympic games, and will
be receiving considerable publicity as a result. One hopes that this will
translate into increased demand for its products and extra business for
Gestetner, which distributes Ricoh products in certain territories.
One company that will be receiving a lot of free publicity for its products
during the summer Olympics is Pentland Group.
Speedo swimwear has been worn by more gold-medal winners than any other
swimwear brand. It ought, therefore, to be prominent at this year's Olympics
and worldwide television coverage of attractive bodies competing in Speedo
costumes ought to increase brand recognition and sales.
Pentland bought various Speedo interests in 1990, and has since
significantly increased them with Speedo operations around the world.
In addition, Pentland owns 20 per cent of the famous sportswear company
Adidas, which also ought to benefit from Olympic publicity. But Speedo and
Adidas products are not just bought by sports people - they have an even
wider appeal as fashion products.
Pentland had net cash of Pounds 273m (equal to 75p per share) at December
31, 1991, mainly due to its disposal of its remaining interest in the Reebok
sports shoe company.
Pentland is, therefore, well poised to ride out any continuing recession and
pick up any 'forced sales' or other bargains of companies whose products it
can develop and promote.
The portfolio will, therefore, purchase 3,500 shares in Pentland at 99p per
share. My wife and I have held Pentland shares in our personal equity plans
since June 1990, when we purchased the shares for 75p each. And my personal
pension scheme took advantage of a drop in Pentland share price in August
1990, to buy shares at 62p each. I took a long-term view with these
purchases, looking for capital growth over the years.
The portfolio will continue to hold cash, ready to take advantage of any
suitable buying opportunities that may appear, due to continuing unsettled
markets.
For example, Fisons, the pharmaceuticals and scientific instruments company,
would have considerable attractions if its share price fell back to around
the 285p level, bearing in mind that its 1991 low was 293p and its 1991 peak
was 515p.
If Fisons did fall to the 285p level - and looked as if it would not fall
much further - then the portfolio would buy 800 Fison shares in the hope of
a turnaround in profits or a takeover bid.
The company has announced a stream of bad news this year, but has all the
bad news been discovered and released - or is there more to come? It is
worth playing safe and waiting to see what happens in the next few months.
Of course, the share price may not fall much further, and the portfolio may
miss being able to buy at its preferred price; but, in the current uncertain
economic climate, I feel it is better to err on the side of caution.
