<DOCNO>FT922-11598</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAEBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (11): Bourses are
deflated by the Bundesbank's refusal to compromise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECOND quarter is traditionally a relatively quiet period for
continental European equities, as shareholders participate in
capital-raising exercises which have been announced with the previous year's
corporate results, or wait for dividends to be paid before making fresh
share purchases.
But this year any share price rises in the April-June period are likely to
be tempered by a higher risk factor, caused by interest rate considerations
and political uncertainty.
Last month, investors began to question the timing of the first interest
rate cut in continental Europe, when an overshooting of money supply growth
and stubbornly high inflation in Germany prompted the Bundesbank to
reiterate its commitment to a stable Deutsche Mark. A growing consensus that
German interest rates would not be reduced until well into the second half
of this year deflated buoyant stock markets throughout the continent.
According to the FT-A World Indices, Europe excluding the UK closed the
first quarter with a gain of 7.1 per cent in local currency terms, compared
with a 10 per cent gain at the beginning of March.
The Bundesbank's refusal to compromise on interest rates, despite evidence
that countries throughout Europe need a looser monetary policy to boost
their flagging economic strength, has prompted speculation that a
realignment in the exchange rate mechanism (ERM) is necessary.
It is difficult to guess who would take the lead. France believes that its
interest rates are artificially high, because of Germany's dominant position
in the ERM; Belgium and the Netherlands have little fiscal flexibility; and
Italy is committed to its 'lira dura' policy. Even Portugal's recent entry
into the wide band of the ERM was not seen as an opportune moment. Current
fears that a revaluation of the D-Mark is inevitable are likely to hang over
continental bourses during the current quarter.
European stock markets are also unsettled by the emergence of vocal minority
parties in France, Italy and Germany. Italian shares slid 7.3 per cent in
March, on fears that the new 'leagues' in the prosperous north would attract
voters away from the leading parties in the general election on April 5,
which would make it harder than usual to form a lasting coalition
government.
France, by contrast, was cheered by the sacking of its first female prime
minister, Edith Cresson, at the start of April. She was replaced by the
finance minister, Pierre Beregovoy, who is liked by the stock market because
of his commitment to improving equity investment in France and his hard line
on inflation.
Lisa Hosking, global strategist at SG Warburg Securities, says France is a
'clear success story', because French companies have become much more
competitive through restructuring, and, through their transatlantic
acquisitions of the past few years, will benefit from the eventual economic
recovery in the US. Also, shares in highly-leveraged companies will react
swiftly to any cut in domestic interest rates.
Germany, whose new-year rally has been capped by the Bundesbank's stance on
inflation, is likely to tread water in the second quarter, until wage
negotiations in the engineering and public sectors are completed. However,
its longer-term outlook remains positive, with earnings expected to recover
in 1993, and the removal of supplementary taxes at the end of July should
revive domestic consumer demand.
Spain proved to be a big disappointment in the first quarter, because
persistently high inflation ruled out the hoped-for cut in interest rates.
In spite of its being one of the cheapest European markets, analysts have
also been put off by the lack of improvement in the wage structure.
</TEXT>
