<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (12): Varied
performance reflects investors' uncertainty about the economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH US stock markets posted mixed results in the first quarter of this
year, the big story was the billions of dollars in newly issued stock that
flooded them.
The rush of stock issues - both initial public offerings (IPOs) by companies
making their debut or returning to the markets, and sales of new shares by
already listed companies - boosted trading volume to high levels. On the New
York Stock Exchange, daily volume averaged 216.5m shares, while on the more
active Nasdaq over-the-counter market it averaged 221m shares.
A record Dollars 30bn was raised via common stock issues and IPOs, compared
with Dollars 9.5bn in the first quarter of 1991, as US companies rushed to
take advantage of relatively firm stock prices and strong demand from
individual and institutional investors for equities.
The pace of new stock issues is unlikely to be maintained, primarily because
the hesitant performance of stock prices in the latter part of the quarter
has made the case for issuing new equity less persuasive.
The best gains of the first quarter were recorded by secondary stocks, with
the Nasdaq composite index rising 6.28 per cent to 602.07 as investors
remained keen on biotechnology, computer technology and healthcare stocks in
particular. Second best was the Dow Jones Industrial Average, which advanced
2.1 per cent to 3235.47. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index, which is most
representative of the US economy, however, showed a net loss for the three
months of 3.2 per cent, ending the period at 403.69.
This varied performance reflects investors' uncertainty about the outlook
for the economy and corporate earnings. The Dow managed a modest gain,
because cyclicals such as Bethlehem Steel, Caterpillar, General Electric and
International Paper were popular early on as investors sought stocks that
would benefit most from economic recovery.
The quarter opened strongly, with the momentum from the December 20 interest
rate cut carrying share prices to a series of new highs in the first six
weeks. Although investors were buying stocks partly in expectation of a
turnaround in the economy, the unattractive yields offered by alternative
investments lured money into equities.
The steady climb in stocks peaked in early March. From then on, prices
oscillated as investors waited for corporate earnings and economic
performance to catch up with share prices.
Monetary policy remained on hold throughout the quarter, with the Federal
Reserve seemingly content that enough had been done to ensure a steady,
inflation-free recovery. Politics reared its ugly head in the form of the
presidential primary season, however, and signs of early weakness in the
Bush re-election campaign cast a cloud over sentiment.
The prognosis for the second quarter is more of the same. Until corporate
earnings display a marked improvement and economic data point to a
sustainable recovery, analysts expect share prices to stay stuck in a
holding pattern.
In Canada, concern about the sluggish economy, the realisation that the pace
of the recovery will lag several months behind the turnaround in the US, and
a recent increase in interest rates, kept a lid on price rises. During the
quarter the Toronto Stock Exchange composite index fell 10 points to
3,412.10. The most troubled sector was financials, with bank stocks hit by
the problems of debt-burdened property giant Olympia &amp; York.
The Mexican stock market, meanwhile, thrived once again, aided by a strong
performance from bank stocks rising sharply in the wake of privatisations.
The Bolsa index rose almost 30 per cent in local currency terms to 1,875.73.
If Bush should lose - Page 13
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
