<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (13): Weak economic
pointers and lower corporate earnings sap confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE MARCH end to the 1991 financial year failed to give Japanese share
prices the boost that had been expected, and the Tokyo stock market closed a
disappointing fiscal year with lingering fears that the Nikkei Stock Average
could plunge even further.
The Nikkei, which in mid-March fell below the 20,000 psychologically
important support level for the first time in five years, closed the first
quarter at a new five-year low of 19,345.95. It had fallen 18.7 per cent
since the beginning of January.
Investor confidence suffered, as a result of further evidence of a weakening
economy and sharp downward revisions of corporate earnings for the year
ended March. Sony, the consumer electronics and entertainment group,
announced that its parent company would post net losses for the first time
since the company was listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange in 1958. Matsushita
Electric Industrial also revised downward its consolidated pre-tax profits
for the year to March to a 43 per cent fall.
Financial scandal involving leading politicians further unnerved investors.
And revelations of stock scandals, in which securities companies had
window-dressed clients' accounts by manipulating loss-making investments,
also depressed confidence.
Meanwhile, an expected interest rate cut by the Bank of Japan failed to
materialise. Political pressures on the central bank to cut the official
discount rate were seen as having set off the move, widely expected in
March. Threats by Mr Shin Kanemaru, the godfather-like figure of the ruling
Liberal Democratic party, to sack Mr Yasushi Mieno, governor of the Bank of
Japan, if the official discount rate was not cut, shocked the financial
community. Additional pressure from cabinet members also discouraged market
participants.
Financial markets reacted coolly to the emergency economic support package,
announced by the government on the last day of March. The package's
proposals to revitalise the stock market was seen as a re-hash of
long-discussed reforms.
Most investors believed that the package indicated a lack of commitment on
behalf of the government to support the stock market. Since proposed rule
changes to allow companies to hold their own shares, calls for higher
dividends, and the establishment of large-lot equity investment funds failed
to convince, the Tokyo market continues to be haunted by a lack of buyers.
Life assurers, traditionally large-lot buyers of equities, are moving from
stock investments into direct corporate lending, and investment trusts are
seeing sharp declines in new-money inflows.
The current weakness is prompting foreign investors, who have been the main
buyers of the Tokyo market during the past year, to reassess allocation of
overseas investments.
In the Pacific Basin, Hong Kong continued its rise, on the back of high
liquidity and improving political sentiment on mainland China. The Hang Seng
index rose 14.9 per cent on the quarter, to 4,938. However, dealers point
out that, as interest rates in the US seem to have hit bottom, the market,
which is led by the US through currency links, holds a possibility of a
short-term correction.
According to Adam Le Mesurier, analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the Thai
market is attractive, because of the favourable economic environment. A
tight grip on monetary policy has curbed domestic demand and inflationary
pressures, leading to an easing in interest rates. The SET index has risen
15.7 per cent, to 823, but still looks promising on a 12-month view.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
