<DOCNO>FT922-11601</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDXBCAD8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (9): A time to pick
stocks with care - Recessions end eventually, and analysts remain convinced
that, in the medium term, equities will outperform fixed-interest and cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS no prize for naming the most bombed-out equity market in the first
quarter of 1992.
Japan, as measured by the 225-share Nikkei Average, ended a truly dismal
three months at its lowest level for more than five years; while the wider
Topix index dropped below 1,400 for the first time since November 1986.
Fund managers overweight in the Japanese market will have a tough time in
quarterly investment reviews with their trustees, and it may take a lot more
than talk of 'buying bargains at the bottom of the market' to sound
convincing. Tokyo has been a sinking bottom.
In terms of total returns in sterling, based on the FT Actuaries World
Index, Japan showed a whopping minus 16.5 per cent in the January-March
quarter - one of only three markets (the others being election-wobbly UK,
and Denmark) to produce a negative return.
Europe, excluding the UK, showed a useful 7.5 per cent return; the Pacific
region, excluding Japan, almost double at 13.5 per cent. Sterling investors
in Mexico continued their roller-coaster ride, with a total return over the
quarter of almost 34 per cent. Malaysia had a very positive 20 per cent; the
French market more than 11 per cent; and Germany, despite problems and fears
over unification, just over 9 per cent.
As ever, stock selection was almost as important as country allocation.
Winners here included media stocks, automobiles, forestry and paper
products, and chemicals; but most markets gave a thumbs-down to banks and
other financial institutions, heavy engineering and textiles. The
capital-goods economic group overall managed almost a 3 per cent total
return, with some tentative signs of companies feeling a little more
optimistic about growth prospects, especially in the US. Italy, like
Britain, had election fever.
Fund managers overweight in Japan had been reduced to praying and hoping
that the authorities there would intervene to at least stabilise the market;
and indeed, there was a move in Tokyo on April 1, when the Bank of Japan cut
the official discount rate by 75 basis points (50 had been the market's
average forecast) and the government unveiled an emergency economic package,
in essence bringing forward some scheduled capital investment. But the
market's first response was a yawn - and a further 4 per cent slide in the
Nikkei Average, the main Japanese index which three years ago threatened to
break through the 40,000 mark.
But is it all doom and gloom ahead? Most market-watchers think not. Despite
the current economic uncertainties, analysts remain convinced that, in the
medium term, equities will continue to outperform fixed-interest and cash.
Recessions, however deep and prolonged (as in the UK) eventually end, and
markets are expected to anticipate the upturns, often by as much as a year
or more. They are even taking some consolation from Japan, arguing that if
the Nikkei was worth buying at 35,000-plus, there must be bargain-basement
deals to be done at around the 20,000 level.
The markets have been a shade over-optimistic about a decline in interest
rates in Europe, given the tough stance of the Bundesbank on German monetary
policy, but the national wage rounds there should be over by mid-year,
holding out the prospect of a cut in German rates, which should allow other
European markets to follow suit. The discipline of the ERM is likely to
herald a period of moderate inflation levels, and the OECD is beginning to
make optimistic forecasts of GNP growth in the main markets for 1993. Some
recent US economic data is modestly encouraging.
The second quarter has started with many markets in a cautious mood, and
investors playing for the short term would do well to be overweight in cash.
It might not be bad advice either for the more cautious fund managers, at
least until the present uncertain investment dust settles.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
