<DATE>920424
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (10): London tumbles
from a Budget-day peak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON'S EQUITY market began the new year much as it had behaved for most of
1991: on a rising trend and full of optimism. Responding to this
bullishness, the FT-SE 100-share index bounded ahead to reach 2,574.8 on
March 10, Budget day, its highest point since November last year.
Thereafter, it never stopped falling, eventually closing the three-month
period some 53 points, or 2.13 per cent, lower.
The reasoning behind the UK market's enthusiasm was easily pinpointed. Apart
from the driving force of a strongly rising Wall Street, there were various
ultimately incorrect assumptions. The big institutions bought the market on
hopes of early signs of economic recovery, which would be followed by
interest rate cuts. The rate cuts would help fuel consumer demand and
business confidence, which in turn would be reflected in an upturn in the
political fortunes of the Tories. They would produce a tax-cutting,
vote-catching budget, followed by a general election victory. Reality proved
otherwise.
Chancellor Norman Lamont's Budget was so badly received that the market
promptly slumped over 52 points in a single session, its heaviest one-day
fall since last year's failed coup in Russia. The City was alarmed at a
public sector borrowing requirement of Pounds 28bn, substantially in excess
of the most pessimistic forecasts. The announcement of the general election
followed within 48
hours, and the market had to face the prospect of an election with UK
interest rates above 10 per cent and with the likelihood that they would
need to rise even more in the not too distant future.
The damage wrought by the recession continued to manifest itself in a
constant stream of disturbing statistics on the economy. Gross domestic
product fell 2.5 per cent in 1991, the biggest year-on-year fall since 1933,
and the longest post-war sequence of quarterly falls.
The quarter did produce some big surprises on the takeover front. The on-off
romance between Midland Bank and Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corporation saw
the two banks betrothed - but the marriage not so far consummated. The rest
of the bank sector was deeply troubled, as worries emerged about property
developers Olympia &amp; York
and Heron Corporation.
A number of cash-raising exercises
materialised, notably Thorn EMI's Pounds 516m rights issue to help finance
its purchase of Virgin Music from Mr Richard Branson. ECC asked its
shareholders to stump up Pounds 214m to enable the group to redeem Dollars
350m of Auction Market Preferred stock in the US.
Corporate results, for the most part, were as expected. Composite insurers
were horribly mauled by mortgage indemnity losses. Royal omitted the final
dividend. Lonrho's dividend cut, sharply lower profits and a series of asset
sales saw the group's share dropped from the Footsie list of top 100 shares.
Politics aside, other factors will increasingly come into play as the year
progresses. Strategists have been highlighting the effects on equities of
the sharp rise in PSBR for the foreseeable future. JP Morgan, the US
investment bank, says: 'The return to large-scale gilt issuance will
pre-empt cash which would otherwise have gone into equities.'
County NatWest, meanwhile, forecasts rights issues of Pounds 11bn over the
coming 12 months. Some analysts argue, however, that market valuations look
increasingly supportive of equities.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
</DOC>
