<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / International Company News: Pechiney hit by aluminium price
fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PECHINEY, the world's largest packaging company and leading aluminium
producer, yesterday announced a 23 per cent decline in operating profits due
mainly to a sharp fall in aluminium prices.
The state-controlled group also announced details of an asset
reorganisation, which will leave its separately quoted 75 per cent
subsidiary, Pechiney International, as a packaging company and put the
aluminium business in the hands of the Pechiney parent. Pechiney is to pay
FFr3.84bn (Dollars 684m) net to take over Pechiney International's aluminium
and trading businesses, representing FFr6.05bn of assets minus FFr2.2bn of
liabilities.
Operating profits at the Pechiney parent fell from FFr6.68bn in 1990 to
FFr5.12bn last year, on sales down by 3 per cent to FFr74.42bn. Net earnings
fell to FFr820m from FFr2.22bn in 1990, excluding extraordinary gains.
In packaging, operating profits rose by 13 per cent, but aluminium earnings
collapsed, from FFr2.5bn to FFr1.48bn.
Mr Jean Gandois, the chairman, said prices were weakened by a sudden influx
of cheap exports from the former Soviet Union, which represented 22 per cent
of the western European market last year. Pechiney is supporting European
Commission moves to negotiate a voluntary restraint accord with the Russian
republic, he said.
Mr Gandois expected Russian exports to diminish this year because stocks
there were low and local demand was increasing. However, worldwide aluminium
stocks were still higher than normal, he said.
The outlook for packaging was good, but overall, the group expected
first-half earnings to fall, with a possible improvement in the second six
months of this year.
Pechiney International also recorded a sharp drop in operating earnings,
down 9 per cent to FFr3.29bn on sales up from FFr43.02bn to FFr45.12bn. Net
profits fell by 26.8 per cent to FFr842m.
The assets transfer means the share of Pechiney International's sales in
packaging will rise from 70 per cent to 85 per cent.
The purpose of the asset sale is to make Pechiney International more
attractive to investors and so help it raise capital, in line with the
French government's decree last year that state industry could sell up to 49
per cent of its shares to the public.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
