Without any consideration of the merits of the conflict he recounts, it
should in effect be noted that:
'unauthorised industrial action' does not exist in this country: no
authorisation, by anyone, is ever necessary to go on strike, and therefore
the employees who went on strike will not be penalised for having done so;
management will rather 'deny pay increases' to those employees on strike
against the very collective bargaining agreement that brought those
increases to them: meaning they cannot eat and refuse the cake;
it is not 'strikers' who are penalised through the pay packet, but those
employees who refuse the pay increases won for them through collective
bargaining by the most representative trade unions in the country. Including
my union.
