<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / Lang introduces softer tone on ruling Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, yesterday inaugurated a more
conciliatory approach by the government to ruling Scotland and called for 'a
change of tone in Scottish politics'.
Presenting his team of four Scottish Office ministers, Mr Lang again
rejected opposition demands for a multi-option referendum on Scotland's
constitutional future but did not rule out referendums as a matter of
principle.
He said no proposal had been put to him by the opposition parties, which
were 'puffing and posturing'.
Mr Lang said the issue of constitutional change had been dealt with in the
general election. The Scottish National party, which fought for Scottish
independence, had won only three seats while the biggest swing in Britain
against Labour, which wanted a devolved Scottish parliament, had been in
Scotland.
'I can see circumstances in which a referendum is a useful mechanism, and
for that reason I'm certainly not willing to rule it out in principle,' he
said. 'But when you start talking about a referendum on three rather woolly
and ill-defined concepts then you identify all kinds of difficulties in
phrasing it, in carrying it out and in deciding what has been decided after
the referendum has taken place.'
Labour and the SNP have demanded a referendum with a choice between the
status quo, a devolved Scottish parliament and independence. A rally will be
staged in Glasgow on Sunday by Scotland United, a group formed by Labour
MPs.
Mr Lang said he was willing to listen to proposals for changes in how
Scotland was governed within the union of the United Kingdom.
His minister of state, Lord Fraser of Carmyllie, the former advocate
general, has responsibility for constitutional matters, in addition to
health and home affairs. Lord Fraser said he did not wish to
'over-emphasise' that responsibility.
Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, the education minister, said he wanted 'calm
and steady' progress in education after the upheavals of recent years. His
fellow junior ministers are Sir Hector Monro and Mr Allan Stewart.
</TEXT>
