<HEADLINE>
FT  24 APR 92 / Co-op Bank calls 'unethical' customers to account
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CO-OPERATIVE Bank is planning to tell corporate customers involved in
blood sports and other activities of which it disapproves to change their
ways or close their accounts.
The action will accompany the bank's publication next month of a formal
ethical policy which will be heralded in an advertising campaign including
television commercials. It follows a market research exercise late last year
in which the bank canvassed the views of 30,000 of its 1.5m customers.
The Co-op said yesterday that up to five 'businesses or commercial
organisations' would be approached to 'discuss whether it is appropriate to
continue banking with us'.
Individuals would not be approached, because the bank assumed that most of
them already shared its values.
The policy would stress attracting new sympathetic customers rather than
targeting ones who did not conform. 'We are confident it will gain us
business,' the bank said. 'This isn't a one-off campaign. It's a question of
stand up and be counted.'
A draft of the ethical policy says the Co-op will not engage in business
with manufacturers, importers or farmers involved in the fur trade.
Equally unacceptable will be those involved in animal experimentation in
toiletries and cosmetics, or animal exploitation such as blood sports,
intensive farming and the breeding of dangerous dogs.
The ethical policy precludes the bank from engaging in business with
manufacturers of tobacco or tobacco products promoted in the less developed
world, with foreign regimes which are in breach of human rights, or with
arms manufacturers supplying these countries.
In addition, it says it will maintain procedures and training programmes to
detect illegal activities such as drug trafficking, money laundering and tax
evasion. It will co-operate with the authorities to stop and prosecute any
such action, and instantly dismiss any staff who are involved.
The Co-op and its parent, the Co-operative Wholesale Society, have long
taken strong stands, including refusing to do business with South Africa and
banning fox-hunting on their land.
The bank issued a Customers' Charter last year under which it refuses to
give out credit information without customers' specific permission.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
